[2] Philippines (Mountain Province)
Date: Fri 30 Nov 2007
Source: Northern Philippine Times [edited]
<http://northphiltimes.blogspot.com/search/label/Mountain%20Province>


The dreaded dengue disease has afflicted 45 residents at latest
count, and the number is rising, health officials said. Nenita
Lizardo, head of the provincial health office reported this statement
saying this was alarming. Lizardo said health personnel earlier
recorded 30 cases in September [2007], but this went up to 45 in
October [2007] with 55 percent of these cases from Bontoc.

Lizardo said that there is a need to advocate the 4-S program against
dengue. The 4-S means' search and destroy' eliminating all breeding
sites for the mosquito, proper waste disposal, covering of water
containers, and cleaning of roof gutters and drains.

The program protection measures advocate use of long sleeves and
pants, installing screens on doors and windows, use of mosquito nets
and adopting a healthy lifestyle to boost resistance. Lizardo advised
constituents to seek consultation, as there was no drug or vaccine
for dengue. "Dengue suspects must be brought to the nearest health
facility immediately, and there should be no self- medication," she
said, adding indiscriminate fogging should only be done during
outbreaks and epidemics [She doubtless meant that fogging should be
focused on areas where dengue virus transmission and cases were
occurring, not indiscriminately anywhere. - Mod.TY].

[Byline: Berlin McIntosh]

--
Communicated by:
ProMED-mail Rapporteur Brent Barrett

[Bontoc is the capital of the Mountain Province, and a map showing
the location of that province can be accessed at:
<http://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Image:Ph_locator_map_mountain_province.png>.
- Mod.TY]

