[3] Indonesia (Bondowoso, Java)
Date: 3 Dec 2007
Source: Jawa Pos [in Indonesian, trans., summarized, edited]
<http://www.jawapos.co.id/index.php?act=detail_radar&id=183162&c=91>


The Kecamatan Kota Bondowoso Territory was not yet free from endemic
[epidemic] dengue fever. As of yesterday [2 Dec 2007], the Kota
Subdistrict contributed most to the number of dengue sufferers,
whereas dengue incidence was lower in the area of mountains like
Sempol, Wringin, or Cermee. Data from the health service indicated
that the number of residents suspected of dengue fever reached 26.
Cases were most frequent in the Kota Subdistrict territory, following
Tegalampel, Grujugan, and the Tenggarang Subdistrict.

--
Communicated by:
ProMED-mail <promed@promedmail.org>

******
[4] Indonesia (Jombang, Java)
Date Fri 30 Nov 2007
Source: Jawa Pos [in Indonesian, trans., summarized., edited]
<http://www.jawapos.co.id/index.php?act=detail_radar&id=182961&c=109>


The attack of the dengue fever in Jombang has not stopped. Yesterday
[29 Nov 2007], at least 3 sufferers who were known positive for
dengue [virus infection] were of concern. The 3 sufferers, who were
treated intensively in the Cukir Community Health Centre, were
residents of the Sentanan Desa Grogol Village, Kecamatan Diwe and
Jombang villages.

Dengue has been seen since last October [?2006 or ?2007] when rains
began. During the period from January [2007] until this October 2007,
there have been 489 dengue fever sufferers, of whom 14 died.

From January until October 2006, the numbers of dengue sufferers who
received medical treatment were 256, of whom 17 died.

--
Communicated by:
ProMED-mail <promed@promedmail.org>

[The numbers of deaths in this reported outbreak are not clear. Have
14 or 17 individuals died? The popular press in Java is currently
reporting outbreaks of febrile disease across the island attributed
to infection by chikungunya virus (see archive no. 20071201.3876)
but, unlike reports of dengue fever, without citation of official
reports of laboratory confirmation. The symptoms of disease caused by
these 5 viruses (chikungunya plus the 4 dengue viruses) can be
similar, underscoring the need for laboratory diagnosis.

An interactive map of Java, Indonesia can be accessed at
<http://encarta.msn.com/map_701513466/Java_(island).html>. - Mod.TY]

******
[5] British Virgin Islands
Date: Fri 30 Nov 2007
Source: BVI News online [edited]
<http://www.bvinews.com/default.asp?sourceid=&smenu=198&twindow=&mad=&sdetail=3899&wpage=1&skeyword=&sidate=&ccat=&ccatm=&restate=&restatus=&reoption=&retype=&repmin=&repmax=&rebed=&rebath=&subname=&pform=&sc=1924&hn=bvinews&he=.com>


The Ministry of Health has today [30 Nov 2007] received confirmation
of 2 cases of dengue in the British Virgin Islands (BVI). Director of
Health Services Dr. Irad Potter says that as the Ministry of Health
continues to monitor the results of other suspected cases of dengue,
it has stepped up its vector control activities through the
Environmental Health Division's Dengue Surveillance Unit. He urges
residents to guard against mosquito bites and to reduce mosquito
breeding around homes and property in order to keep the number of
cases in the BVI to a minimum.

"Blood samples have been sent to the Caribbean Epidemiology Centre
(CAREC) to confirm the status of other suspected cases of dengue, and
we are awaiting the results. Of the 14 specimens that have been sent
off for testing, 9 have come back; 2 of the 9 are positive. The
specimens take at least 4-6 weeks to be processed. Persons suspected
of having dengue are treated based on their clinical presentation by
their doctor," Dr. Potter said.

Dr. Potter noted that in light of recent outbreaks in the region,
persons who have traveled to Puerto Rico, Dominican Republic,
Martinique and Guadeloupe and are experiencing painful flu-like
symptoms of high fever, nausea and painful body aches within 3 to 14
days of their travel should seek medical attention.

Dengue virus, which can also cause a rash in infected persons, is
spread through the _Aedes aegypti_ mosquito commonly found in the
BVI. The Director of Health Services advised that due to the
heightened awareness in the sub-region related to dengue, suspected
cases are being investigated and followed up to rule out or confirm
the presence of the virus.

All _Aedes aegypti_ inspectors are up and about surveying public and
private spaces. However, mosquitoes reproduce at a rapid rate.
Therefore, surveys of private and work spaces must be completed by
residents themselves to break the mosquito cycle.

In September [2007], the Environmental Health Division issued an
advisory putting residents and visitors of the BVI on high alert in
response to dengue outbreaks in Puerto Rico and Guyana.

--
Communicated by:
ProMED-mail Rapporteur Brent Barrett

[It is not clear from this report if the 2 dengue virus infections
were acquired elsewhere or on the British Virgin Islands.

An interactive ProMED health map of the British Virgin Islands can be
accessed at: <http://healthmap.org/promed?v=18.4,-64.6,7>. - Mod.TY]


******
[6] St. Maarten
Date: Thu 29 Nov 2007
Source: De Telegraaf [in Dutch, trans., edited]


This year [2007], there have been 18 cases of dengue found on the
Antillean island of St. Maarten. This is the highest number of cases
of this disease ever detected on the island in a year. Therefore, a
warning has been declared.

Earlier this month [November 2007], Aruba has taken measures to
prevent a dengue outbreak.

--
Communicated by:
ProMED-mail <promed@promedmail.org>

[A map of St. Maarten showing its location in the Caribbean can be accessed at:
<http://graphicmaps.com/webimage/countrys/namerica/caribb/stmartin.htm>.
- Mod.TY]

