[7] Brazil (Campinas)
Date: Sat 24 Nov 2007
Source: Cosmo On Line [in Portuguese, trans., summarized Mod.TY, edited]
<http://www.cosmo.com.br/cidades/campinas/integra.asp?id=213454>


Campinas has officially confirmed 5035 dengue cases since January
[2007]. However, the Secretary of Health is expecting cases of this
disease to total 13 000, taking into account the 8000 notified
suspected cases which are not expected to be laboratory confirmed
within the medium-term. "Despite this, we have opted to consider
these cases as positive," explained the Health Surveillance
Coordinator (COVISA), Salma Balista.

She pointed out that among these cases, some may not be dengue, but
as the absolute majority [of these cases] were notified at the peak
of the epidemic in the 1st semester of 2007, chances are that they
are really dengue. "From the point of view of [dengue] control and
prevention measures, this does not change anything, as actions are
launched based on suspected [disease], since serological results [for
confirmation] take time. But in terms of a map of the actual
situation, and the definition for the patient, [this] is important,"
observed Salma.

"It is always difficult to know the exact number of cases in a large
epidemic, such as we are facing [now]. But, with 5000, 10 000 or 15
000 cases, the logistics of preventive work is the same," affirmed
the Secretary of Health, Jose Francisco Kerr Saraiva.

He recalled that, as determined by the ministry and the Secretary of
Health, those municipalities which had an incidence of over 300
[dengue] cases per 100 000 inhabitants -- Campinas had an incidence
coefficient of 475 cases per 100 000 inhabitants -- do not need to do
more than carry out serological tests to confirm occurrences [of
dengue cases]. This disease can be confirmed on the basis of
clinico-epidemiological criteria.

Since the beginning of 2007, COVISA has received 21 000 notifications
of suspected cases of the disease. Of the 5035 officially
[laboratory] confirmed cases, 20 were DHF and 65 were dengue with
complications resulting in 2 deaths. Another 2 deaths included
[individuals] living in other cities of the region, who died in
Campinas hospitals.

[Byline: Dema Medeiros]

--
Communicated by:
LISAS
<http://lisas.anvisa.gov.br>

