[8] Brazil (Alagoas)
Date: Sat 24 Nov 2008
Source: Gazeta [in Portuguese, trans., summarized Mod.TY, edited]
<http://www.prensaescrita.com/diarios.phpcodigo=POR&pagina=http://gazetaweb.globo.com>


An open public meeting will be held this Saturday [24 Nov 2007] with
representatives of the State Committee to Combat Dengue and the State
Public Ministry with the objective of stimulating the public to
combat, in their residences, the breeding sites of the mosquito that
transmits dengue [virus], referring to "D Day", the national [day]
for mobilization against dengue.

From January [2007] until the beginning of this month [November
2007], 11 207 classical dengue [fever] cases were registered in the
state [Alagoas - Mod.MPP]; 454 DHF cases with complications were
registered, with 12 deaths in the municipalities of Maceio, Colonia
Leopoldina, Palmeira dos Indios, Penedo and Santana do Mundau.

The municipalities in which 80 percent of the cases were concentrated
are considered priority [areas] including: Maceio, Marechal Deodoro,
Arapiraca, Penedo, Santana do Ipanema, Teotonio Vilela, Maragogi,
Palmeira dos Indios, Delmiro Gouveia, Paripueira, Barra de Santo
Antonio, Coqueiro Seco, Satuba, Barra de Sao Miguel, Santa Luzia do
Norte, Messias, Rio Largo, Pilar and Uniao dos Palmares.

--
Communicated by:
LISAS
<http://lisas.anvisa.gov.br>

******
[9] Europe
Date: Wed 28 Nov 2007
Source: Tehran Times [edited]
<http://www.tehrantimes.com/index_View.asp?code=158053>


A mosquito that can carry the deadly dengue fever virus is moving
north and has crossed the Swiss Alps, health authorities in the
canton of Aargau said.

They said it had not yet been determined whether the tiger mosquitoes
[_Aedes albopictus_] found so far are isolated individuals or part of
an established local colony.

_Aedes albopictus_ can also carry the chikungunya virus, which
infected more than 160 people in northern Italy earlier this year
[2007]. In Switzerland, it had only been found previously south of
the Alps, in the canton of Ticino.

The Swiss health ministry plans to make chikungunya, which was
described for the 1st time in Tanzania in 1952, a mandatory
reportable disease from next year [2008].

The mosquito is also present in southern France and parts of Spain,
as well as the United States, but the outbreak of chikungunya in
Italy is thought to have been the 1st outside the tropics.

Health experts meeting in Stockholm in September [2007] said European
countries must work to control tiger mosquito populations, but the
situation was not alarming.

--
